### Describe the bug

When creating a PR from a fork, 
Error: failed to create pull request: GraphQL error: The baseRefName is invalid.
```
gh --version                                                             î‚² 1 î‚² 20:06:48 
gh version 0.11.1 (2020-07-28)
https://github.com/cli/cli/releases/tag/v0.11.1
```

### Steps to reproduce the behavior

1. Fork a repo
1. Make a change in master
1. `gh pr create --base <PARENT_USERNAME>:master --title "Title" --body "Body"`

### Expected vs actual behavior

**Expected**
Create pull request successfully.

**Actual**
Error: failed to create pull request: GraphQL error: The baseRefName is invalid.

HTTP Proxy Log shows GraphQL call:
```
{
  "query": "\n\t\tmutation PullRequestCreate($input: CreatePullRequestInput!) {\n\t\t\tcreatePullRequest(input: $input) {\n\t\t\t\tpullRequest {\n\t\t\t\t\tid\n\t\t\t\t\turl\n\t\t\t\t}\n\t\t\t}\n\t}",
  "variables": {
    "input": {
      "baseRefName": "<PARENT_USERNAME>:master",
      "body": "Body",
      "draft": false,
      "headRefName": "<FORK_USERNAME>:master",
      "repositoryId": "*****",
      "title": "Title"
    }
  }
}

## Response
{
  "data": {
    "createPullRequest": null
  },
  "errors": [
    {
      "type": "VALIDATION",
      "path": [
        "createPullRequest"
      ],
      "locations": [
        {
          "line": 3,
          "column": 4
        }
      ],
      "message": "The baseRefName is invalid."
    }
  ]
}
```

**SOLUTION**
The GraphQL request works successfully after removing `<PARENT_USERNAME>:`

### Describe the bug

Using http.REST to perform a DELETE request, which results in a 204, fails in the json.Unmarshal call as the input []byte has a len length == 0

Location in code: https://github.com/cli/cli/blob/a6495a8c0d4679df94cd287bcd346781901ce1ae/api/client.go#L154

Use-case is to remove a Github app grant using the equivalent of the following CURL command:

```
curl -u <CLIENT_ID:CLIENT_SECRET> -X DELETE https://api.github.com/applications/<CLIENT)ID>/grant -d '{"access_token": "<CLIENT_TOKEN>"}'
```

Per spec and implementation, the [revoke a grant for an application](https://developer.github.com/v3/apps/oauth_applications/#revoke-a-grant-for-an-application) returns 204 on success.

NOTE: Currently GH does not issue http.REST("DELETE", ...) commands which is which never should as an issue.

### Steps to reproduce the behavior

```
	http := api.NewClient(
		api.AddHeader("Authorization", fmt.Sprintf("Basic %s", Base64AppID())),
		api.AddHeader("Content-Type", "text/plain"),
	)

	req := struct {
		AccessToken string `json:"access_token"`
	}{
		AccessToken: token,
	}

	var resp interface{}

	path := fmt.Sprintf("applications/%s/grant", ClientID())

	body := bytes.NewBuffer([]byte{})
	json.NewEncoder(body).Encode(req)

	err := http.REST("DELETE", path, body, &resp)
	if err != nil {
		return err
	}
```

2. View the output '....'

3. See error

The returned err value returned from the Unmarshal call:

```
(*json.SyntaxError)(0xc000708060)(unexpected end of JSON input)
```

### Expected vs actual behavior

The expected behavior would be that a 204 resp is handled correctly, by not attempting to unmarshal.  

A simple fix to address the issue could be to add the following check to return early

```
	if resp.StatusCode == 204 && resp.ContentLength == 0 {
		return nil
	}
```

Within the existing code:

```
// REST performs a REST request and parses the response.
func (c Client) REST(method string, p string, body io.Reader, data interface{}) error {
	url := "https://api.github.com/" + p
	req, err := http.NewRequest(method, url, body)
	if err != nil {
		return err
	}

	req.Header.Set("Content-Type", "application/json; charset=utf-8")

	resp, err := c.http.Do(req)
	if err != nil {
		return err
	}
	defer resp.Body.Close()

	success := resp.StatusCode >= 200 && resp.StatusCode < 300
	if !success {
		return handleHTTPError(resp)
	}

	if resp.StatusCode == 204 && resp.ContentLength == 0 {
		return nil
	}

	b, err := ioutil.ReadAll(resp.Body)
	if err != nil {
		return err
	}

	err = json.Unmarshal(b, &data)
	if err != nil {
		spew.Dump(resp, b, err)
		return err
	}

	return nil
}
```

A clear and concise description of what you expected to happen and what actually happened.

